ass=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Period\n!Life expectancy in<br />Years\n!Period\n!Life expectancy in<br />Years\n|-\n|1950\u20131955\n|40.7\n|1985\u20131990\n|57.0\n|-\n|1955\u20131960\n|44.2\n|1990\u20131995\n|60.0\n|-\n|1960\u20131965\n|47.2\n|1995\u20132000\n|63.7\n|-\n|1965\u20131970\n|49.3\n|2000\u20132005\n|66.7\n|-\n|1970\u20131975\n|46.3\n|2005\u20132010\n|69.1\n|-\n|1975\u20131980\n|52.2\n|2010\u20132015\n|71.2\n|-\n|1980\u20131985\n|54.3\n|\n|\n|}\nSource: ''UN World Population Prospects''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://esa.un.org/unpd/wpp/DataQuery/|title=World Population Prospects \u2013 Population Division \u2013 United Nations|last=|date=|year=|website=Esa.un.org|pages=|language=|format=|access-date=15 July 2017|quote=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160919061238/https://esa.un.org/unpd/wpp/DataQuery/|archive-date=19 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===HIV/AIDS===\n:Prevalence rate: less than 0.1% (adults, 102nd in world, 2001 est.); 0.01% (2014 est.)\n:People living with HIV/AIDS: 12,000 (85th in world, 2007 est.)\n:Deaths: fewer than 500 (87th in world, 2007 est.); about 700 (2014 est.).\n\n===Major infectious diseases===\n:Degree of risk: high\n:Food or waterborne diseases: bacterial and protozoal diarrhea, hepatitis A and E, and typhoid fever\n:Vectorborne diseases: dengue fever and malaria are high risks in some locations\n:Water contact disease: leptospirosis\n:Animal contact disease: rabies (2005)\n\n==Ethnic groups==\n{{bar box\n|title=Ethnic groups in Bangladesh<ref name=\"CIATONGA\">{{cite web|url= https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/bg.html|title= South Asia ::BANGLADESH|publisher= CIA The World Factbook}}</ref>\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Bengali people|Bengali]]|Black|98.0}}\n{{bar percent|[[Ethnic minorities]]|blue|1.1}}\n{{bar percent|Uncertain|red|0.9}}\n}} \nThe vast majority (about 98.5%) of Bangladeshis are of the [[Bengali language|Bengali]] ethno-linguistic group. This group also spans the neighboring Indian province of [[West Bengal]]. Minority ethnic groups include [[Meitei people|Meitei]], [[Tripuri people|Tripura]], [[Marma people|Marma]], [[Tanchangya people|Tanchangya]], [[Barua (Bangladesh)|Barua]], [[Khasi people|Khasi]], [[Santhal people|Santhals]], [[Chakma people|Chakma]],[[Rakhin people]], [[Garo (tribe)|Garo]], [[Biharis]], [[Kurukh people|Oraons]], [[Munda people|Mundas]] and [[Rohingya people|Rohingyas]].\n\nCommunities of [[Persian people|Persian]] and [[Iranic peoples]] mainly reside in the city of [[Chittagong]] and are the descendants of migrants that immigrated during the [[Pakistani]] dominion over [[Bangladesh]], and also from the British Partition of 1947. Some are descendants of the Persian settlers during the medieval era of the [[Bengal Sultanate]], most [[Iranic peoples]] living in Chittagong are either mainly or fully integrated into Bengali society, and have even influenced the Chittagonian language as a whole.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Role of the Persian Language in Bengali and the World Civilization: An Analytical Study |url=https://www.uits.edu.bd/research/journal/v1i2/7-Persian.pdf |website=Uits.edu |access-date=4 August 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031134308/http://uits.edu.bd/research/journal/v1i2/7-Persian.pdf |archive-date=31 October 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Bangladesh - Ethnic groups |url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Bangladesh/Ethnic-groups |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Chittagong City - Banglapedia |url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Chittagong_City |website=En.banglapedia.org |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[Biharis]] are [[Urdu]]-speaking, non-Bengalis who emigrated from the state of [[Bihar]] and other parts of northern India during the [[partition of India|1947 partition]].  They are concentrated in the [[Dhaka]] and [[Rangpur, Bangladesh|Rangpur]] areas and number some 300,000.<ref name=dw>{{cite web|title=Socio-economic Problems of the Urdu Speaking Residents at Mohammadpur|url=http://www.dwatch-bd.org/ggtp/Research%20Reports/research3.pdf|publisher=Democracy Watch|accessdate=12 April 2011}}</ref><ref name=ju>{{cite web |last=Persoob |first=Tasmia |title=The Forgotten Community: Camp Based Urdu Speaking People in Bangladesh |url=http://akira-foundation.org/Documents/fellow%20product%20%28Tasmia%29.pdf |publisher=Jahangirnagar University |accessdate=12 April 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322152732/http://akira-foundation.org/Documents/fellow%20product%20%28Tasmia%29.pdf |archivedate=22 March 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref> In the 1971 independence war many of them sided with Pakistan, as they stood to lose their positions in the upper levels of society.<ref name=\"country study\">[http://countrystudies.us/bangladesh/29.htm Ethnic and Linguistic Diversity], Bangladesh: A Country Study, Edited by James Heitzman and Robert Worden, Washington: GPO for the Library of Congress, 1989.</ref>  Hundreds of thousands went to Pakistan and those that remained were interned in [[Stranded Pakistanis|refugee camps]]. Their population declined from about 1 million in 1971 to 600,000 in the late 1980s.<ref name=\"country study\"/> [[Refugees International]] has called them a \"neglected and stateless\" people as they are denied citizenship by the governments of Bangladesh and Pakistan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.refugeesinternational.org/content/publication/detail/7828/ |title=Refugees of Nowhere: The Stateless Biharis of Bangladesh |date=15 February 2006 |website=Refugees International |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070614045741/http://www.refugeesinternational.org/content/publication/detail/7828/ |archive-date=14 June 2007}}</ref> As nearly 40 years has passed, two generations of Biharis have been born in these camps. Biharis were granted Bangladeshi citizenship and voting rights in 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title= Citizenship for Bihari refugees |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/go/pr/fr/-/2/hi/south_asia/7407757.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |date=19 May 2008 |access-date=21 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nBangladesh's tribal population was enumerated at 897,828 in the 1981 census.<ref name=\"country study\"/> These tribes are concentrated in the [[Chittagong Hill Tracts]] and around [[Mymensingh]], [[Sylhet]], and [[Rajshahi]]. They are of Sino-Tibetan descent and differ markedly in their social customs, religion, language and level of development. They speak Tibeto-Burman languages and most are Buddhist or Hindu.<ref name=\"country study\"/> The four largest tribes are [[Chakma people|Chakmas]], Marmas, Tipperas, [[Tanchangya people|Tanchangya]],  and Mros. Smaller groups include the Santals in Rajshahi and Dinajpur, and Khasis, Garos, and Khajons in Mymensingh and Sylhet regions.<ref name=\"country study\"/>\n\nThere are small communities of [[Meitei people|Meitei]] people in the Sylhet district, which is close to the Meitei homeland across the border in [[Manipur]], India.\n\nThere is a small population of [[Rohingya]] refugees from [[Myanmar]] near the border in the southeast. There are 28,000 living in two UN refugee camps in [[Cox's Bazar]] as well as some 200,000 \"unregistered people of concern\" living outside of the camps.<ref>[http://www.unhcr.org/cgi-bin/texis/vtx/page?page=49e487546 2010 Regional Operations Profile - South-East Asia], [[UNHCR]], 2010.</ref>\nThe refugee crisis originated in the early 1990s when the first wave numbering some 250,000 of the predominantly Muslim ethnic group fled persecution from their home in Rakhaine\u2014Myanmar's western-most state. Bangladesh seeks to repatriate the refugees back to Myanmar.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rohingya refugees in Bangladesh refuse repatriation |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gAUv3NW-WgdhhVGoQX3y7xbRroTw |agency=[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]] |date=30 December 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Language==\n{{bar box\n|title=Languages of Bangladesh (2011) <ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/>\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Bangla language|Bangla]]|Blue|98.8}}\n{{bar percent|Other|Orange|1.2}}\n}}\n\n{{Main|Languages of Bangladesh}}\n* Official language: [[Bengali language|Bengali]] (also known as Bangla)\n* Other languages often considered dialects of Bengali: [[Chittagonian language|Chittagonian]], [[Sylheti language|Sylheti]], [[Rohingya language|Rohingya]], [[Tangchangya language|Tangchangya]], [[Chakma language|Chakma]], and [[Rangpuri language|Rangpuri]].<ref name=\"ethnologue.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/country/BD/languages|title=Bangladesh|website=Ethnologue|accessdate=23 June 2019}}</ref>\n* Other [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indic languages]]: [[Bishnupriya Manipuri language|Bishnupriya Manipuri]], [[Assamese language|Assamese]], various [[Bihari languages]]\n* [[Tibeto-Burman languages]]: [[A'Tong language|A'Tong]], [[Chak language|Chak]], [[Koch language|Koch]], [[Garo language|Garo]], [[Megam language|Megam]], [[Meitei language|Meitei Manipuri]], [[Mizo language|Mizo]], [[Mru language|Mru]], [[Pangkhua language|Pangkhua]], [[Rakhine language|Rakhine]]/[[Marma Language|Marma]], [[Kok Borok language |(Tipra/Tripura/Tripuri)]], [[Reang language|Riang]], [[Tippera language|Tippera]], [[Usoi language|Usoi/Uchoi]], various [[Chin languages]]<ref name=\"ethnologue.com\"/>\n* [[Austroasiatic languages]]: [[Khasi language|Khasi]], [[Koda language|Koda]], [[Mundari language|Mundari]], [[Pnar language|Pnar]], [[Santali language|Santali]], [[War language|War]]<ref name=\"ethnologue.com\"/>\n* [[Dravidian languages]]: [[Kurukh language|Kurukh]]<ref name=\"ethnologue.com\"/>\n* Other languages: English ''(spoken and known widely in upper-class & politics)'', [[Arabic language|Arabic]] ''( sometimes spoken and known by many Muslims, due to Islam being the primary religion)'', [[Hindi]]/[[Urdu]] ''(understood by some, and spoken by [[Biharis]])''\n\n==Religion==\n{{see also|Islam in Bangladesh|Hinduism in Bangladesh|Buddhism in Bangladesh|Christianity in Bangladesh}}\n;Population trends for major religious groups in Bangladesh (1951\u20132011)\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions of Bangladesh (2013)<ref name=\"CIATONGA\"/>\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Islam in Bangladesh|Islam]] |green|90.39}}\n{{bar percent|[[Hinduism in Bangladesh|Hindu]]|Orange |8.3}}\n{{bar percent|Other (includes [[Buddhism in Bangladesh|Buddhist]], [[Christianity in Bangladesh|Christian]])|blue|0.9}}\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"margin:auto;\"\n|- style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! Religious<br>group\n\n! Population <br>% 1951.<ref name=\"bangladeshgov\">{{cite web|url=http://hrcbmdfw.org/files/22/population_data/entry489.aspx |title=Bangladesh- Population census 1991: Religious Composition 1901-1991|date=2 August 2016|website=Bangladeshgov.org}}</ref>\n! Population <br>% 1961<ref name=\"bangladeshgov\"/>\n! Population <br>% 1974<ref name=\"bangladeshgov\"/>\n! Population <br>% 1981<ref name=\"bangladeshgov\"/>\n! Population <br>% 1991<ref name=\"bangladeshgov\"/>\n! Population <br>% 2001<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.banbeis.gov.bd/bd_pro.htm |title=Bangladesh: at a glance |website=Bangladesh Bureau of Educational Information and Statistics (BANBEIS) |access-date=13 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160403214141/http://www.banbeis.gov.bd/bd_pro.htm |archivedate=3 April 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n! Population <br>% 2011<ref>{{cite web |url=http://203.112.218.69/binbgd/RpWebEngine.exe/Portal?BASE=HPC2011_long&lang=ENG |title=Population & Housing Census 2011 |website=Bangladesh Bureau of Statistics (BBS) |access-date=13 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160603182032/http://203.112.218.69/binbgd/RpWebEngine.exe/Portal?BASE=HPC2011_long&lang=ENG |archive-date=3 June 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"background:Green;\"| Islam\n|78.9 %||80.4 %||85.4 %||86.6 %||88.3 %|| 89.7% ||90.39\n|-\n! style=\"background:Orange;\"| Hinduism\n|22 %||18.5%||13.5%||12.1 %||10.5 %|| 9.2% || 8.3%\n|-\n! style=\"background:Gold;\"| Buddhism\n| 0.7 %|| 0.7 %||0.6 %||0.6 %||0.6 %||0.7 % || 0.6%\n|-\n! style=\"background:DodgerBlue;\"| Christianity\n|0.3 %||0.3 %||0.2 %||0.3 %||0.3 %|| 0.3% || 0.4%\n|-\n! style=\"background:GreenYellow;\"| Other religions/No religion\n|0.1 %||0.1 %||0.2 %||0.3 % ||0.3 %|| 0.1% || 0.1%\n|}\n\n==Genetics==\nBangladesh has the world's highest frequency of the [[Haplogroup M (mtDNA)|M]] form of [[mitochondrial DNA]]. This genetic variant spans many continents, and is the single most common mtDNA haplogroup in Asia.<ref>Ghezzi et al. (2005), [http://www.nature.com/ejhg/journal/v13/n6/full/5201425a.html Mitochondrial DNA haplogroup K is associated with a lower risk of Parkinson's disease in Italians], European Journal of Human Genetics (2005) 13, 748\u2013752.</ref> In [[Bangladesh]] it represents about 83% of maternal lineages.<ref name=\"Metspalu\">[http://www.biomedcentral.com/content/pdf/1471-2156-5-26.pdf Mait Metspalu et al., ''Most of the extant mtDNA boundaries in South and Southwest Asia were likely shaped during the initial settlement of Eurasia by anatomically modern humans''. BMC Genetics, 2004]</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Literacy rate Bangladesh.png|thumb|right|Literacy rates in Bangladesh districts]]\nBangladesh has a [[literacy rate]] of 72.9 percent as of 2018. 75.7 percent for males and 70.09 percent for females.\n{{-}}\n==Migrants==\n\nAccording to the United Nations, there were 1,500,921 international migrants in Bangladesh in 2017.\n\nTheir most common countries of origin were as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"width:25em;\"\n! colspan=2|International migrants in Bangladesh in 2017\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Myanmar}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 239,742\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Malaysia}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 208,406\n|-\n| {{Flagu|China}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 166,646\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Indonesia}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 156,500\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Laos}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 90,253\n|-\n| {{Flagu|United States}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 47,103\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Nepal}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 39,988\n|-\n| {{Flagu|India}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 35,250\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Great Britain}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 34,266\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Bahrain}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 30,877\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Vietnam}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 28,176\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Cambodia}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 20,109\n|-\n|colspan=2|<center><small>Source: [[United Nations ]]</small>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/en/development/desa/population/migration/data/estimates2/docs/MigrationStockDocumentation_2017.pdf|title= Migrant Stock by Origin and Destination|date=2019|accessdate=4 October 2019}}</center>\n|}\n\n\nAt the same time, the United Nations also enumerated the Bangladesh diaspora as 4,499,919 persons.\n\nThe most common countries where Bangladeshi migrants are located were as follows:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"width:25em;\"\n! colspan=2|International migrants from Bangladesh in 2017\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Saudi Arabia}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1,377,072\n|-\n| {{Flagu|United Arab Emirates}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1,044,505\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Kuwait}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 381,669\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Malaysia}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 365,600\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Oman}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 276,518\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Great Britain}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 228,353\n|-\n| {{Flagu|United States}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 279,021\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Qatar}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 183,386\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Italy}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 100,743\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Singapore}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 83,279\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Bahrain}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"| 80,457\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Canada}} || style=\"text-align: